<HEAD>Excavators Dig Up Marble Statue in Pompeii</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POMPEII, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archaeologists unearthed a small marble
statue buried in the eruption of <LOCATION>Mount Vesuvius</LOCATION> in 79 <LOCATION>A.D.</LOCATION>, the
first such find in 13 years, newspapers reported <DATE>Sunday</DATE>.
   The statue, which depicts a baby boy riding a dolphin, was found
<DATE>Saturday</DATE> in the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> of the <PERSON>Casti Amanti</PERSON>, near the center of the
abandoned city, <PERSON>Il Mattino</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Naples</LOCATION> and other papers reprted.
   Archaeologists said the statue was apparently to be used to
decorate a fountain in the house, but that Vesuvius erupted before
workers had a chance to set it in place. Experts said traces of
paint coloring the hair blond and eyebrows black made the find even
more valuable.
   They believe the <ORGANIZATION>House of Casti Amanti</ORGANIZATION> was owned by a baker, who
lived on one side and kept a shop on the other.
   The last statue to be found in <LOCATION>Pompeii</LOCATION> was a bronze dug up in
<DATE>1977</DATE>.
</TEXT>
