<HEAD>Bandits Bind, Gag Custodians, Rob Treasures at Herculaneum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAPLES, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masked gunmen bound and gagged unarmed
guards early <DATE>Saturday</DATE> at <LOCATION>Herculaneum</LOCATION>, a Roman city destroyed when
Mount Vesuvius erupted in 79 <LOCATION>A.D.</LOCATION>, and stole hundreds of treasures,
news reports said.
   <PERSON>Baldassare Conticello</PERSON>, the superintendent of the archaeological
areas of <LOCATION>Herculaneum</LOCATION> and nearby <LOCATION>Pompeii</LOCATION>, said the inventory of the
stolen goods was still incomplete, the Italian news agency <ORGANIZATION>AGI</ORGANIZATION>
reported.
   The missing items included about 200 gold bracelets and
earrings, a first century bronze vase in the form of a woman's head
and a 32-inch silver-and-copper inlaid bronze statue of Bacchus, he
said.
   At least four bandits wearing ski masks surprised four night
watchmen at their station, <ORGANIZATION>AGI</ORGANIZATION> quoted investigators as saying. The
custodians were forced at gunpoint to turn over the keys to a
building that houses hundreds of artifacts, the news agency said.
   It said the custodians were tied up and their mouths taped with
bandages. After a few hours, one of the guards was able to free
himself and sounded an alarm.
   <PERSON>Conticello</PERSON> said sale of the stolen goods would be difficult
since they were cataloged. But he said it was possible someone had
commissioned the holdup to enrich a personal collection.
   <PERSON>Walter Mazzitti</PERSON>, the head of Archeoclub of <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION>, an
organization of people interested in archaeology, decried what he
called a lack of adequate security at major ruins in the <LOCATION>Naples</LOCATION>
area and syggested that guards there should be armed.
   <LOCATION>Herculaneum</LOCATION>, along the Bay of <LOCATION>Naples</LOCATION> and with the volcano at its
back, included the villas of wealthy ancient Romans. Its ruins,
discovered in <DATE>1709</DATE>, are considered better preserved than those at
the more extensive complex at <LOCATION>Pompeii</LOCATION>, which was also destroyed by
<ORGANIZATION>Mount Vesuvius</ORGANIZATION>' eruption.
</TEXT>
