<TEXT>
   National Gallery of Art, <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>D.C.</LOCATION> -- "The
Sculpture of <LOCATION>Indonesia</LOCATION>" -- More than 130 objects from the
eighth through 15th centuries, the classical period of
Indonesian art. Works include Buddhist and Hindu stone
sculpture, bronzes, small figural objects of gold and silver,
and ceremonial objects. Of special interest is a life-size
<ORGANIZATION>Buddha</ORGANIZATION>, one of 504 made for the largest Buddhist temple ever
built, <LOCATION>Borobudur</LOCATION>. Fourth Street at <ORGANIZATION>Constitution Avenue NW</ORGANIZATION>,
through <DATE>Nov. 4</DATE>. The show then travels to <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>'s Museum of
Fine Arts (<DATE>Dec. 9</DATE>, 1990-March 17, <DATE>1991</DATE>); <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>'s
Metropolitan Museum of Art (<DATE>April 21-Aug</DATE>. 18, <DATE>1991</DATE>); and <LOCATION>San
Francisco</LOCATION>'s Asian Art Museum (<DATE>Sept. 28</DATE>, 1991-Jan. 5, <DATE>1992</DATE>).
                                                                                                       

   Art Institute of <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>: "The <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION> Skyscraper:
Selections From the Permanent Collection" -- More than 50
drawings and models document the development of the
skyscraper in the <LOCATION>Windy City</LOCATION>. Included are drawings of
Murphy/Jahn's <ORGANIZATION>Northwestern Terminal Tower</ORGANIZATION> (1976-87); early
prints for <PERSON>Burnham</PERSON> and Root's Rookery; and fantasy drawings
from the <ORGANIZATION>Chicago Architectural Club</ORGANIZATION>'s <DATE>1983</DATE> competition to
redesign the tops of <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION> skyscrapers. Michigan Avenue at
<ORGANIZATION>Adams Street</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>July</DATE> 23-Dec.31.
                                                                                                       

   <ORGANIZATION>IBM Gallery of Science</ORGANIZATION> and Art, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>: "Rediscovering
Pompeii" -- More than 200 frescoes, sculptures, vessels,
games, articles of jewelry and everyday objects from
first-century <LOCATION>Pompeii</LOCATION>. The exhibit also features more than 20
interactive computer programs enabling visitors to take an
electronic "walk" through the city's buildings, and see a
time-lapse sequence of the eruption of <LOCATION>Mount Vesuvius</LOCATION> in 79
A.D. 590 <LOCATION>Madison Ave.</LOCATION>, <DATE>July 12-Sept</DATE>. 15.
                                                                                                       

   <PERSON>Max Protetch Gallery</PERSON>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>: "Alan Sonfist: Art of the
Environment" is a 25-year overview of works by a
site-specific artist who does not inflict hostile piles of
rusting metal on squawking neighborhoods. The 20-some art
works include bronze castings of endangered oaks done for a
private estate outside <LOCATION>Florence</LOCATION>, and a series of collages
showing the process of his art, which often involves the
re-creation of historic landscapes. 560 Broadway, through
<DATE>July 27</DATE>.

   MUSIC/FESTIVAL
                                                                                                       

   <ORGANIZATION>Santa Fe Opera</ORGANIZATION>'s 34th season runs through <DATE>Aug. 25</DATE> and
features performances of <ORGANIZATION>Puccini</ORGANIZATION>'s "La Boheme" (<DATE>July 11</DATE>, 20,
30, <DATE>Aug. 2</DATE>, 7, 14, 21 and 25); <PERSON>Mozart</PERSON>'s "Cosi Fan Tutte"
