Euridice," with <PERSON>Marilyn Horne</PERSON> as <PERSON>Orfeo</PERSON> (<DATE>July 14</DATE>, 18, 27, <DATE>Aug.
4</DATE>, 8, 17 and 23); <PERSON>Strauss</PERSON>'s "Ariadne Auf Naxos" (<DATE>July 21</DATE>, 25,
<DATE>Aug. 3</DATE>, 9, 16 and 22); and East German composer <PERSON>Siegfried
Matthus</PERSON>'s "<PERSON>Judith</PERSON>," with <PERSON>Stephanie Sundine</PERSON> in the title role
(<DATE>July 28</DATE>, <DATE>Aug. 1</DATE>, 10, 18). <ORGANIZATION>Santa Fe Opera Theater</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Santa Fe</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>N.M.</LOCATION> (505) 982-3855.
                                                                                                       

   <ORGANIZATION>Santa Fe Chamber Music Festival</ORGANIZATION>'s 18th season runs through
<DATE>Aug. 20</DATE>. Highlights include: premiere performances of two
commissions by Pulitzer Prize-winning composers <PERSON>Ellen Taaffe
Zwilich</PERSON> and <PERSON>Ned Rorem</PERSON>; festival debut performances by the
Moscow-based <ORGANIZATION>Shostakovich String Quartet</ORGANIZATION> quartet; a piano
recital in honor of <PERSON>Aaron Copland</PERSON>'s 90th birthday; and
baroque compositions played on period instruments. <ORGANIZATION>St.
Francis Auditorium</ORGANIZATION>. (505) 982-1890.
                                                                                                       

   Festival d'Ete International de <LOCATION>Quebec</LOCATION>: The Italian
coloratura mezzo-soprano <PERSON>Cecilia Bartoli</PERSON> makes her North
American debut with a program of <PERSON>Mozart</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Rossini</ORGANIZATION> arias,
among them <PERSON>Sesto</PERSON>'s aria from "La Clemenza di Tito," and the
show-stopping "Tanti Affetti" from "La Donna del Lago." The
<ORGANIZATION>Quebec City Symphonic Orchestra</ORGANIZATION> is conducted by <PERSON>Simon
Streatfield</PERSON>. Grand Theatre de <LOCATION>Quebec</LOCATION>, <DATE>July 12</DATE>. (418)
692-4540.
                                                                                                       

   Mostly Mozart Festival: <PERSON>Ms. Bartoli</PERSON> then travels to
<ORGANIZATION>Lincoln Center</ORGANIZATION> to sing one of the master's concert arias, a
tune from "Cosi fan Tutte," and "Tanti Affetti." Jean <PERSON>Pierre
Rampal</PERSON> also appears on the program with a flute concerto by
<ORGANIZATION>Pleyel</ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON>Gerard Schwarz</PERSON> conducts. <DATE>July 17</DATE>, 18.
   Mozart's comic one acter, "The Impresario," features
<PERSON>Frances Ginsberg</PERSON> and <PERSON>Sally Wolf</PERSON> slugging it out as rival
prima donnas and <PERSON>Vincent Cole</PERSON> as the frustrated producer.
This <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> and <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, with the <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> performance
telecast on <ORGANIZATION>PBS</ORGANIZATION>. Alicia de Larrocha playing <ORGANIZATION>Mozart's Piano
Concerto</ORGANIZATION> in C major, K. 503, rounds out the program. <PERSON>Avery
Fisher Hall</PERSON>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. (212) 874-2424.
