<P>
Millionaire oilman <PERSON>J. Paul Getty</PERSON> in <DATE>1954</DATE> purchased a large ranch-style home on 
65 acres in <LOCATION>Malibu</LOCATION>, in which he opened a museum to display art objects he had 
been collecting. As his collection grew, <PERSON>Getty</PERSON> built a new museum, designed as 
a reconstruction of a Roman seaside villa that was buried in an eruption of <LOCATION>Mt. 
Vesuvius</LOCATION> in AD 79. Completed in <DATE>1974</DATE>, the museum contains 38 galleries of art, 
including antiquities from <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Rome</LOCATION>, as well as <ORGANIZATION>Renaissance</ORGANIZATION> and Baroque 
