<HL> Italy Gets Back Six Stolen Artworks Found Last Year </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP </CO>
<DATELINE> ROME (AP)  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six stolen artworks discovered a year ago hidden in the <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION> home of an Italian have been returned to <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Cultural Ministry</ORGANIZATION> announced yesterday. 

   A 15th-century triptych by <PERSON>Gabriele di Francesco</PERSON> was among the works. 
The painting, in three side-by-side panels, was stolen in <DATE>1985</DATE> from the altar of the Cathedral of Roniglione, 33 miles north of <LOCATION>Rome</LOCATION>. 

   A 15th-century painting by <PERSON>Francesco Raibolini</PERSON>, three 17th-century compasses with ivory cases, and <PERSON>Francesco Netti</PERSON>'s <DATE>1800</DATE> "Procession of Penance During the <DATE>1794</DATE> Eruption of Vesuvius" also were recovered. 
They were stolen from <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION> between <DATE>June 1983</DATE> and <DATE>August 1984</DATE>. 

   The Italian news, <ORGANIZATION>ANSA</ORGANIZATION>, said the works were found in the home of <ORGANIZATION>Giambattista Ongaro</ORGANIZATION>. 
It quoted ministry officials as saying several other works that had been exported illegally from <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION> also were found in the home. 

   No charges were filed against <PERSON>Mr. Ongaro</PERSON>. 
The ministry said there is no evidence to link him to the thefts. 

</TEXT>
