<TEXT>
      HOLIDAY SPECTACLE
   Christmas Tree and Baroque Creche -- The Metropolitan Museum's always-stunning annual display features a 20-foot tree and an 18th-century manger adorned with a collection of about 180 carved Neapolitan creche figures. 
Medieval <PERSON>Sculpture Hall</PERSON>, 82nd Street and Fifth Avenue. 
Wednesdays through <DATE>Sundays</DATE> <TIME>9:30 a.m.-5:15 p.m.</TIME> and <DATE>Tuesdays</DATE> <TIME>9:30 a.m.-8:45 p.m.</TIME> 
Through <DATE>Jan. 3</DATE>. 
Suggested contribution is <MONEY>$5</MONEY>; <MONEY>$2.50</MONEY> for children and senior citizens. (212) 535-7710. 

   Elsewhere in town: At <ORGANIZATION>Herald Center</ORGANIZATION> (34th Street at <LOCATION>Broadway</LOCATION>, sixth floor), more than 300 painted terra-cotta figurines populate a Nativity scene made by a <LOCATION>Naples</LOCATION> craftsman expressly for this <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> showing. 
Nearby is a smaller 18th-century creche. 
Mondays through <DATE>Saturdays 10</DATE> <TIME>a.m.-7 p.m.</TIME> and <DATE>Sundays</DATE> <TIME>noon-6 p.m.</TIME> 
Through <DATE>Jan. 10</DATE>. 
Admission <MONEY>$2</MONEY>; <MONEY>$1.50</MONEY> for children, senior citizens and groups. (212) 695-3738. 
And in the window of the <ORGANIZATION>Alitalia</ORGANIZATION> ticket office (666 Fifth Avenue), some 200 people, animals and miniature objects are arrayed against a representation of <ORGANIZATION>Mount Vesuvius</ORGANIZATION> and classical ruins in an antique creche from a private collection in <LOCATION>Naples</LOCATION>. 
Through <DATE>Jan. 10</DATE>. 

   <ORGANIZATION>Citibank Station</ORGANIZATION> -- This Victorian-style structure, typical of a turn-of-the-century train depot, soars 32 feet into the atrium at <LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Citicorp Center</ORGANIZATION> through <DATE>Dec. 31</DATE> (closed Christmas Day). 
A peek through the 6-foot-high viewing areas on each of its three sides reveals the treat: 10 tracks of model trains whizzing through three miniature scenes of <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> life. 
Conceived and designed by Broadway set designer <PERSON>Clarke Dunham</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Citibank Station</ORGANIZATION> is open daily from 10 a.m.-9 p.m. (free). 
Lexington Avenue at 53rd Street. (212) 559-2330. 

   ART
   <ORGANIZATION>Walters Art Gallery</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Baltimore</LOCATION>: "Stories From <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s Past" -- The 2,000-year-old archaeological treasures in this exhibit were created to celebrate the dead, but today provide a vibrant picture of life in <LOCATION>Han dynasty China</LOCATION>. 
Statues in bronze, terra cotta and stone, ceramic tiles and rubbings -- all excavated from tombs in <LOCATION>Sichuan</LOCATION> province -- depict couples kissing, farmers toiling, acrobats and musicians entertaining. 
The piece de resistance is an intricately worked bronze "money tree." 

   The show, organized by the Chinese Culture Center of <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>, will be at the museum (600 <LOCATION>North Charles St.</LOCATION>) through <DATE>Jan. 10</DATE>. 
It then travels to <ORGANIZATION>Cornell University</ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON>Herbert F. Johnson Museum</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Ithaca</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.Y.</LOCATION> (Jan. 26-March 13), <ORGANIZATION>UCLA</ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON>Frederick S. Wight Gallery</PERSON> (<DATE>April 3-May 22</DATE>) and the <LOCATION>Phoenix</LOCATION> Art Museum (<DATE>June 18-Aug</DATE>. 21). 

   Western Reserve Historical Society: <PERSON>Jerry Siegel</PERSON> and <PERSON>Joe Shuster</PERSON> were <LOCATION>Cleveland</LOCATION> high school students when they created Superman; now they're being honored by their former hometown with an exhibit of Superman memorabilia that spans 50 years of "truth, justice and the American way." 
Included is the first drawing of the "man of steel," by <PERSON>Mr. Shuster</PERSON>. 10825 <LOCATION>East Boulevard</LOCATION>. 
Through <DATE>Feb. 29</DATE>. 

   DANCE
   <ORGANIZATION>Nikolais Dance Theatre/Murray Louis Dance Company</ORGANIZATION>: Modern dance pioneers <PERSON>Alwin Nikolais</PERSON> and <PERSON>Murray Louis</PERSON> try something new -- sharing a season. 
The togetherness extends beyond splitting the bill -- dancers from both troupes join forces to perform three of the works scheduled. 
And that's not all that's new: The five-week engagement includes plenty of premieres, three by "Nik" and two by <PERSON>Murray</PERSON>. 
Joyce Theater, 175 Eighth Ave. (at 19th St.), <LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION>. 
Tonight through <DATE>Jan. 17</DATE>. (212) 242-0800. 

   MUSIC
   <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> Opera presents two new productions: <LOCATION>Mascagni</LOCATION>'s rarely performed comic opera "L'Amico Fritz" and <ORGANIZATION>Gilbert &amp; Sullivan</ORGANIZATION>'s operetta "Ruddigore." 
"Fritz" is the story of an inveterate bachelor (tenor Tonio Di Paolo) who falls in love with shy Suzel (soprano <PERSON>Katherine Luna</PERSON>). 
<ORGANIZATION>Cal Stewart Kellogg</ORGANIZATION> conducts. 
<DATE>Dec. 19</DATE>, 22, 26, 28; <DATE>Jan. 1</DATE>, 5, 7, 9, 11, 15 and 17. 

   "Ruddigore," a satire of a Gothic novel, stars <PERSON>Thomas Goerz</PERSON> as <PERSON>Robin Oakapple</PERSON>, <PERSON>Paul Austin Kelly</PERSON> as <PERSON>Richard Dauntless</PERSON> and <PERSON>William Parcher</PERSON> as <ORGANIZATION>Sir Despard Murgatroyd</ORGANIZATION>. 
<ORGANIZATION>Randolph Mauldin</ORGANIZATION> conducts. 
<DATE>Dec. 21</DATE>, 26, 31; <DATE>Jan. 3</DATE>, 8, 10, 12, 16, 19, 23, 25 and 30. 
Eisenhower Theater, <ORGANIZATION>Kennedy Center</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>D.C.</LOCATION> (202) 822-4757. 

